{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538979","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538979"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:35:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:35:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16424"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16424","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16424"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.02,0.39,0.1,0.49]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9115"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83301"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9115","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9115"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16424"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68291"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1343"},{"type":"tags","id":"5320"},{"type":"tags","id":"11059"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21653"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28294"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28295"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83301","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/83301"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for review of her hormone replacement therapy (HRT), which she has been taking for 12 years. She was initially started on HRT for severe menopausal symptoms including hot flushes and night sweats. She reports good symptom control and wishes to continue her current regimen. She has a medical history of hypertension and osteoarthritis. Her medications include oral combined oestrogen-progesterone HRT and irbesartan. She has never smoked. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her blood pressure is 142/88 mmHg.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most significant concern regarding her continued HRT use?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increased risk of bowel cancer","Increased risk of gallbladder disease","Increased risk of endometrial cancer","Increased risk of osteoporosis","Increased risk of stroke"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has been on HRT for 12 years, which is longer than currently recommended. While HRT can be highly effective for managing menopausal symptoms, the risks and benefits must be carefully balanced, particularly with long-term use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased risk of stroke\u003C/strong\u003E is the most significant concern in this case. The risk of stroke increases with both age and duration of HRT use, particularly after 10 years of use. This patient also has hypertension, which compounds her stroke risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased risk of bowel cancer\u003C/strong\u003E is not correct as HRT actually reduces the risk of colorectal cancer. The Women\u0027s Health Initiative (WHI) trial demonstrated that combined HRT was associated with a 37% reduction in colorectal cancer risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased risk of endometrial cancer\u003C/strong\u003E is not a major concern in women taking combined HRT, as the progesterone component provides endometrial protection. This risk is mainly relevant to women taking oestrogen-only HRT.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased risk of osteoporosis\u003C/strong\u003E is not correct as HRT actually provides protection against osteoporosis. However, this benefit is lost after discontinuation of therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased risk of gallbladder disease\u003C/strong\u003E, while present with HRT use, is not the most significant concern in this clinical scenario given the duration of use and the patient\u0027s cardiovascular risk factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe current recommendation is to use HRT for the shortest duration necessary to control symptoms, typically 5-10 years. Regular review is essential to assess the ongoing risk-benefit ratio, with consideration of gradual discontinuation or dose reduction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Long-term use of hormone replacement therapy (\u003E10 years) increases the risk of stroke and venous thromboembolism.","The benefits of hormone replacement therapy for menopausal symptoms typically outweigh risks only in the first 5-10 years after menopause.","Regular review of hormone replacement therapy is essential, with the aim to use the lowest effective dose for the shortest duration."],"references":["Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. Managing menopausal symptoms [Internet]. Melbourne: RANZCOG; 2023 [cited 2024 Nov 25]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/Managing-Menopausal-Symptoms.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68291"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16424"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68291","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68291"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-03T06:53:23+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-03T06:54:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9115"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83301"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"desc